poem:
The Bluscrue in the Movement

The gearlings twined within the case;
tick-tack the mainspring softly sang.
All brass was blue with burnish-grace;
and pivot-pins went clink-a-clang.

Mind, child of cogs, the Bluscrue's guile;
its threadling teeth will keenly bite.
That glimmergrub of tempered file
will catch at polish-bright at night.

I took my loupe and lever-knife;
a clicker-pick, adjuster-wheel;
my oiler-pen, my pegwood life,
and wound my will to wary wheel.

Through gearglow wood of plates I crept;
for blued screw in a movement slept,
beneath the balance-bridge it lay,
a threadling shade of steel-blue sway.

Hush—whirr-whirr—out the Bluscrue wound;
it bobbled, thread by thread it bound;
its lever-lash made clinkling sound,
its eyelet flamed a ruby round.

Click-clack! I set the steadfast stake;
the springblade sang ker-ching ker-ching;
I threaded through its twisty wake,
and snipped the scuttle-spring to sting.

The Bluscrue slumped; its buzz unspun;
the gearglade breathed; the beat begun;
I bagged the boltling, one by one,
and soothed each beat that had begun.

Now gearlings twine within the case;
tick-tack the mainspring softly sings;
the blued screws sleep in burnish-grace,
and pivot-pins go clangless rings.

Murmuration over Stubble

By dusk the stubble fields were dun,
while hushwinds combed the furrowed ground;
a sable-skein unspooled the sun
in whirrs and whorls that wove around.

“Take heed, my seed,” said Gaffer Grange;
“the Murmurlord makes dark of day;
it gulfs the air with flitter-change,
and sips your step to stray away.

Now take this windspoke, willow-strong,
a thresher’s stave with hushbound twine;
prime pulse and pace; keep heart-song long;
let gritglebe guard your grainward spine.”

I stepped where stubblestems went scritch;
the duskdrift droned a throaty thrumm;
sky’s soot-braid bent to skirl and hitch,
with flisk and flutter, whush and humm.

Outcurled a beak from billow-swarm,
a Mask-of-Many, murk-enthroned;
it sheared the field to feather-storm,
it crackled: krr; bleak brr; low drone.

I winded wide the windspoke’s arc,
and split the swirls with swish-a-swish;
the Murmurlord unstitched its dark,
fell featherfirst in flinder-fish.

Home strode I through the stubble-gleam,
with one black plume for token-tale;
Old Grange cried out, “O harvest-dream!”
and beat his bowl with spoon and pail.

By dusk the stubble fields lie dun,
while hushwinds comb the furrow-mound;
and dreams of dusk unspooling sun,
with whirrful whorls still woven round.
